3. Implement and Evaluate The SVR Model ¶

1) Choose technical indicators¶

the selected technical indicators include

technical indicator description formula
momentum general trend over a certain period price(t) - price(t-n)
rolling average mean of prices during a certain period sum(price(t-n),...,price(n))/n
rolling standard deviation std of prices during a certain period std(price(t-n),...,price(t))
average true range volitility of the market ATR(t)=((n-1) * ATR(t-1)+Tr(t))/n
triple exponential moving average smooth the insignificant movements TR(t)/TR(t-1) where TR(t)=EMA(EMA(EMA(Price(t)))) over n days period

note:

  • rolling average and rolling std are all critical part in calculating the bollinger band which provides good prediction on the range the stock price would oscillate
  • Tr(t)=Max(Abs(High-Low), Abs(Hight-Close(t-1)), Abs(Low-Close(t-1)) Since the purpose of this project is for demonstrating the predictive power of a traditional regression model and the deep learning model in a comparative manner rather than to squeeze every bit of performance out of the models, only a selected few of technical indicators were utilized in training the model. Provided that adding more indicators could potentially improve the performance.
In [48]:
# moving average
def calc_technical_indicators(df_input, window_size=10):
    df = df_input.copy()
    df['momentum'] = df['adj close'] - df['adj close'].shift(window_size)
    df['rolling average'] = df['adj close'].rolling(window_size).mean()
    df['rolling std'] = df['adj close'].rolling(window_size).std()
    df['tr1'] = abs (df['high'] - df['low'])
    df['tr2'] = abs (df['high'] - df['close'].shift())
    df['tr3'] = abs (df['low'] - df['close'].shift())
    df['true range'] = df[['tr1', 'tr2', 'tr3']].max(axis=1)
    df['average true range'] = df['true range'].ewm(span=window_size).mean()
#     df['tema'] = df['close'].ewm(span=10).mean()
    df = df.fillna(method='backfill')
    df = df.drop(columns=['tr1', 'tr2', 'tr3', 'true range'])
    return df
df_svr = calc_technical_indicators(df_normalized_std, 8)

2) Create training set and testing set¶

In [49]:
def create_train_test_datasets(df_input, window_size, features=[]):
    if features:
        number_of_features = len(features)
        dataset = df_input.copy()[features].values
    else:
        number_of_features = len(df_input.columns)
        dataset = df_input.copy().values
    window_size = window_size + 1
    result = []
    for index in range(len(dataset) - window_size): # maxmimum date = lastest date - sequence length
        result.append(dataset[index: index + window_size]) # index : index + 22days
    result = np.array(result)

    row = round(0.9 * result.shape[0]) # 90% split
    data_train = result[:int(row), :] # 90% date, all features

    X_train = data_train[:, :-1] 
    y_train = data_train[:, -1][:,-1]
    print('Shapes: \n processed data : {}\n data_train - {}\n X_train - {}\n y_train : {}\n'.format(result.shape, data_train.shape, X_train.shape, y_train.shape))

    X_test = result[int(row):, :-1] 
    y_test = result[int(row):, -1][:,-1]
    print('Shapes: \n X_test - {}\n y_test : {}\n'.format(X_test.shape, y_test.shape))

    X_train = np.reshape(X_train, (X_train.shape[0], X_train.shape[1], number_of_features))
    X_test = np.reshape(X_test, (X_test.shape[0], X_test.shape[1], number_of_features))
    print('X_train has a shape of {} | X_train sample at 1: \n{}'.format(X_train.shape, X_train[1]))
    print('y_train has a shape of {} | y_train sample at 1: \n{}'.format(y_train.shape, y_train[1]))
    
    return [X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test]

4. Implement and Evaluate the LSTM Model ¶

1) Build the structure of model¶

  • dropout = 0.3
  • epochs = 100
  • LSTM 256 > LSTM 256 > Relu 32 > Linear 1
In [64]:
window_size_lstm = 1
num_of_features = len(df_normalized_minmax.columns)

def build_model(layers):
    d = 0.3
    model = Sequential()
    
    model.add(LSTM(256, input_shape=(layers[1], layers[0]), return_sequences=True))
    model.add(Dropout(d))
        
    model.add(LSTM(256, input_shape=(layers[1], layers[0]), return_sequences=False))
    model.add(Dropout(d))
        
    model.add(Dense(32,kernel_initializer="uniform",activation='relu'))        
    model.add(Dense(1,kernel_initializer="uniform",activation='linear'))
    
    # adam = keras.optimizers.Adam(decay=0.2)
        
    start = time.time()
    model.compile(loss='mse',optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    print("Compilation Time : ", time.time() - start)
    return model

model = build_model([num_of_features, window_size_lstm])
model.summary()
plot_model(model)

3) Denormalize the data, calculate the score and visualize the results¶

In [66]:
train_predict = model.predict(X_train)
test_predict = model.predict(X_test)

y_train_denorm = min_max_scaler.inverse_transform(y_train.reshape(-1, 1))
train_predict_denorm = min_max_scaler.inverse_transform(train_predict)
y_test_denorm = min_max_scaler.inverse_transform(y_test.reshape(-1, 1))
test_predict_denorm = min_max_scaler.inverse_transform(test_predict)

# print(y_predict_denormalized[:5], '\n\n', y_test_denormalized[:5])
train_score = sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train_denorm[:,0], train_predict_denorm[:,0]))
test_score = sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_denorm[:,0], test_predict_denorm[:,0]))
print('train score and test score are respectively {} and {}'.format(train_score, test_score))

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
plt.plot(y_test_denorm, color='C1', label='test')
plt.plot(test_predict_denorm, color='C2', label='predicted')
plt.xlabel('timeline')
plt.ylabel('stock price')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.show()
